com.quest.glue.api.services
Interface SSHConnection2

All Superinterfaces:
CommandLineConnection2
public interface SSHConnection2
extends CommandLineConnection2

Interface provided to agents once a line-based terminal connection has been established, such as an SSH session with a remote host. This interface allows clients to send and receive lines of text across the wire.

For example, on a UNIX connection the list of processes could be retrieve with the following code: 

 class MyCallback implements Callback {
     public void established(Connection connection) {
         connection.sendLine("ps");
         String line = connection.readLine();
         while ( line != null ) {
             handleProcess(line);
             line = connection.readLine();
         }
     }
 }

Note that an established SSH connection is not the same as an interactive terminal. In particular, a terminal will not be assigned to the user and many logon scripts may not be run.

Since:
5.5.5.5

execute

void execute(java.lang.String command,
             java.io.OutputStream stdout,
             java.io.OutputStream stderr,
             long timeoutMillis)
             throws SignalledExitException,
                    NonZeroExitCodeException,
                    ConnectionBrokenException,
                    java.util.concurrent.TimeoutException,
                    java.lang.InterruptedException
Send a line of text over the wire. The output of the command will be piped through the provided streams while the command executes. Once finished, the commands return code will be returned.

Agent code can pass null for any output stream that they are not interested in. FglAM will log any unhandled stdout or stderr messages at debug and error levels, respectively, so that the output will not be lost.

Agents are encouraged to provide buffered output streams (if they provide any stream at all) to ensure data can be processed quickly.

This command will be run by the user's configured shell in non-interactive mode. No terminal will be assigned for this command. The exact environment available to commands executed in this way is dependent on the remote machine's configuration.

Executing commands in this manner is synonymous with running the following: 

 ssh user@host `command`

command - The command to send
stdout - Stream to which the connection will write the command's stdout data

getArchitecture

java.lang.String getArchitecture(long timeoutMillis)
Try to guess the canonical architecture type of the remote system. This method assumes that the target system is some flavour of UNIX and supports the uname command. It is a convenience method for executing uname -m and mapping the results through CanonicalNameService.getArchitecture(String arch).

If any errors are detected the failure will be logged on the agent's behalf and this method will return null.

Parameters:
timeoutMillis - The number of milliseconds to wait before failing
Returns:
The results of uname -s mapped into Quest's canonical operating system type
See Also:
CanonicalNameService.getArchitecture(String arch)

getHostName

java.lang.String getHostName(long timeoutMillis)
Attempt to return the canonical host name for this machine. This method assumes that the target system is some flavour of UNIX and supports the uname command. It is simply a convenience method for executing uname -n, parsing the results, and logging any thrown exceptions.

If the remote system is a windows box running an SSH server this command will fail in undefined ways, the most likely way being successfully executing but returning garbage as the hostname.

If any errors are detected the failure will be logged on the agent's behalf and this method will return null.

Parameters:
timeoutMillis - The number of milliseconds to wait before failing
Returns:
The results of uname -n or null if an error occurred

getOperatingSystemType

Try to guess the canonical operating system type. This method assumes that the target system is some flavour of UNIX and supports the uname command. It is simply a convenience method for executing uname -s and mapping the results through CanonicalNameService.getOperatingSystemType(String name).
